# How has the G7 responded to the crisis in Ukraine and what specific actions have they taken to support the country?

## Summary
The G7 has taken action to help Ukraine respond to the crisis by establishing a "coordination mechanism" to repair, restore and defend its critical infrastructure <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>. To this end, government officials have delivered 400 generators to hospitals nationwide, with another 1,100 expected from a joint project with the World Bank and 170 more from the World Health Organization <font color=#FF3399>[2]</font>. Additionally, the European Commission has proposed an 18 billion-euro financial support package for the country <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. Sergei Kovalenko, CEO of Yasno, reported that Ukraine faced a 32% deficit in projected power supply on Monday, necessitating scheduled blackouts <font color=#FF3399>[4]</font>. While Russia has pulled out of the deal due to the attack on its Black Sea fleet <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>, the EU has provided 500 power generators to Ukraine to address the energy crisis <font color=#FF3399>[4]</font>. Furthermore, SIPRI data shows that Russia's share of the global arms export market has declined by 5 percent from 2017 to 2021 and its exports have fallen by a quarter, primarily due to decreasing demand from India and Vietnam <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>.

